{"questionId":"11927","questionHtml":"<p>Explain why <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"28 - T\">\n  <mn>28</mn>\n  <mo>−</mo>\n  <mi>T</mi>\n</math></span> can be modeled by an exponential function.</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p>Rearranging the model gives <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"28 - T = a{b^t}\">\n  <mn>28</mn>\n  <mo>−</mo>\n  <mi>T</mi>\n  <mo>=</mo>\n  <mi>a</mi>\n  <mrow>\n    <msup>\n      <mi>b</mi>\n      <mi>t</mi>\n    </msup>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span><em><strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>So&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"28 - T\">\n  <mn>28</mn>\n  <mo>−</mo>\n  <mi>T</mi>\n</math></span> can be modeled by an exponential function.&nbsp;<em><strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;AG</strong></em></p>\n<p><em><strong>[2 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"11927","referenceCode":"EXM.1.AHL.TZ0.21a","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Explain why 28 − T can be modeled by an exponential function.","paper":"1","level":"AHL","questionNumber":"a","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 1]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 4—Statistics and probability","Topic 4—Statistics and probability","AHL 4.13—Non-linear regression"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}}}